{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5205","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:38 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:38 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">Comparative constructions are formed by taking the short form of an adjective and adding the suffix <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་</span>. The term being compared is followed by <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལས་</span>. The markers <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལས་</span> and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ནས་</span> are the two forms of the ablative that are used in Literary Tibetan, but in the spoken language it is only <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ནས་</span> that denotes the ablative, whereas <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལས་</span> is reserved for comparative constructions.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདི་ལས་མང་ང་(མང་བ་)འདུག</span> “There is more than that.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཆང་སྦི་རག་ལས་ཞིམ་པ།</span> “<em>Chang</em> is better than beer.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དེབ་དེ་འདི་ལས་ཡག་ག (ཡག་པ།)</span> “That book is better than this one.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གཡག་མཛོ་ལས་ཆེ་བ་འདུག་གས།</span> “Are yaks bigger than <em>dzo</em>?”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གཡག་མཛོ་ལས་ཆེ་བ།</span> “Yaks are bigger than <em>dzo</em>!” </li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The auxiliary <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདུག་</span> is optional in declarative sentences, whereas it is obligatory in negative and interrogative sentences.</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Note that the position of the item being compared is not fixed; it may also come first:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྦི་རག་ལས་ཆང་ཞིམ་པ།</span> “Compared with beer, <em>chang</em> is better.”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">When the adjective is an attribute of the subject, another construction is also commonly used: the short form of the adjective is followed by the auxiliary <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གི་རེད།</span>.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདི་ལས་མང་གི་རེད།</span> “There is more than this.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཆང་སྦི་རག་ལས་ཞིམ་གྱི་རེད།</span> “<em>Chang</em> is better than beer.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གཡག་མཛོ་ལས་ཆེ་གི་རེད།</span> “Yaks are bigger than <em>dzo</em>.” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལྷ་ས་པེ་ཅིང་ལས་བསིལ་གི་རེད།</span> “It’s colder in Lhasa than in Beijing.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྣ་ལོ་བཞོན་ན་ཡག་གི་རེད།</span> “It’s better to ride a <em>nalo</em> (gentle, hornless yak).”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གནམ་གྲུའི་ནང་ལ་བཏང་ན་གོང་ཆེ་གི་མ་རེད་པས།</span> “Won’t it cost more to send it by air?”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Tibetan has no special constructions for marking comparatives of inferiority. “Less than” is expressed simply reversing the order of comparison or by using an opposite adjective.</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">For example, to translate the expression “He is less poor than I am,” Tibetan would use these constructions, based on context:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ང་ཁོང་ལས་སྐྱོ་གི་རེད།</span> “I’m poorer than him.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོང་ང་ལས་ཕྱུག་གི་རེད།</span> “He’s richer than me.” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོང་ང་ལས་སྐྱོ་བ་ཡོད་མ་རེད།</span> “He isn’t poorer than me.”</li> </ul>","title":""}]}
